<font color="#FF0000">THE WAR AT HOME</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec 28  7:33:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Andy,<br><br>
If we could have won the war, we would have.<br><br>
You cannot seperate the internal political issues in<br>
a country with the wars it fights in. It can be argued that<br>
we could have won a conflict in vietnam (though if you<br>
read about military strategies for a &quot;peoples&quot; war<br>
you can see that it is not as easy as one might think.<br><br>
The war we never could have won was the war for the hearts<br>
and minds of the American Public. It has been said that<br>
the main force that ended the war was the movement of<br>
middle class mothers who did not want their children to<br>
die. That was the less vocal part of the anti-war movement,<br>
but a most powerful force with political clout. They<br>
led their husbands, and friends to do all that was done<br>
to make the war have to be fought on two fronts.<br><br>
This is why you cannot leave the fighting to the military. <br>
All wars need to be fought on the battle front, and<br>
all wars need the internal support of the people at home.
